mame-system-media — licensing and preservation notice
=======================================================

This repository contains two kinds of material with different rights. Please
read both sections before reusing anything.


1. Original work by Dave Rand
-----------------------------

The documentation (all README files), the CP/M CBIOS I authored, the bootable
disk images I formatted and curated, my own disk-recovery images, and the
photographs of my own hardware are:

    Copyright (c) 2026 David L. Rand

    Licensed under the Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International License
    (CC BY 4.0). You are free to share and adapt this material for any purpose,
    provided you give appropriate credit.

    Full license text: https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/legalcode
    SPDX-License-Identifier: CC-BY-4.0

Suggested attribution:

    "Dave Rand — github.com/davidlrand/mame-system-media"


2. Third-party material preserved for emulation and research
------------------------------------------------------------

Some files are the intellectual property of their original manufacturers or of
those manufacturers' customers, and are NOT mine to license. The products
involved were all discontinued decades ago. These items include:

    - colonial-sb80/bootrom.bin
          Colonial Data Services boot ROM (1982).

    - the Colonial Data CP/M 2.2 (02.15) CBIOS contained in
      colonial-sb80/disks/sb80-1k.td0

    - the customer application and data files (TMS) contained in
      colonial-sb80/disks/sb80-1k.td0

    - Toshiba Corporation's stock CP/M BIOS, as contained in the disk images
      toshiba-t250-t200/disks/T-250/Toshiba-original-v2.20.* and
      toshiba-t250-t200/disks/T-200/t200-boot-v2.21.* (and the ser-10133
      variant). (My own replacement boot ROMs and BIOS in this folder are
      covered by section 1 above.)

    - colonial-sb80/docs/microcomputing-1982-09-sb80-review.pdf
          A four-page excerpt (the SB-80 review "Everything You Need On a Single
          Board" by Terry Kepner) from Microcomputing, September 1982, pp. 58-61.
          Published by 1001001, Inc. / Wayne Green Inc.; the magazine ceased in
          1984 and the publisher is long defunct.

    - third-party CP/M utilities (an ARC archiver suite, an assembler, BASIC,
      etc.) contained in trs80-model3-cpm/disks/mycpm-model3.imd. (My own CP/M
      BIOS and the disks I built/curated are covered by section 1 above; the
      Model III ROMs are not redistributed here -- they load from MAME's stock
      trs80m3 romset, and the "CP/M Cheap" circuit modification is the work of
      Bill Brewer, 80 Microcomputing, March 1983.)

They are included in good faith for historical preservation, research, and use
with the MAME emulator, on the basis that the original product is decades out of
production and otherwise unavailable. No copyright claim is made over them, and
their inclusion does not transfer any rights.

If you hold rights to any of this material and wish it removed, please open an
issue or contact me, and I will take it down promptly.

Underlying CP/M is the work of Digital Research, Inc.; no Digital Research
material is redistributed here beyond what was customarily present on a working
system disk of the period.
